                                <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#f0f0f0" width="20%" valign="top"><b>Release Notes:</b></td>
                <td id="customfield_11841-157760-value" class="value" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="80%">      <p><b>Posit reports:</b></p>

<ul>
	<li>Identify missing codes in ca.map_surgery_crosswalk and ca.map_definitive_surgery_prioritization <a href="https://posit-connect.prod.aws.npowermedicine.com/content/663a7f3d-a68a-4234-a2eb-50ba1c22016e" class="external-link" rel="nofollow noreferrer">report</a></li>
</ul>


<p><b>Missing codes that were added/updated:</b></p>

<ul>
	<li>In <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/11PcA62hLqXPhfYRvFwTsq2R7Tw5i0vP-d3E6prw5uNg/edit?gid=1627450865#gid=1627450865" class="external-link" rel="nofollow noreferrer">map_surgery_crosswalk</a> → After discussion with Brad, anything without a suffix (like “lu”, “br”) is likely colorectal  codes or else entry errors and should not be included in our coding. This accounted for all codes initially found that weren’t included in his crosswalk, besides the “ot” suffixed ones, which should also be considered errors and excluded from any mapping.
	<ul>
		<li><b>DECISION</b>: Code to exclude these non-suffixed values was added to primary_site_surgery.R. No changes to the map_surgery_crosswalk were made/needed.</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li>In <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/11PcA62hLqXPhfYRvFwTsq2R7Tw5i0vP-d3E6prw5uNg/edit?gid=1043759049#gid=1043759049" class="external-link" rel="nofollow noreferrer">map_definitive_surgery_prioritization</a> → Met with Christer. Only lung cancer had missing mapping. We created a new surgery category (“Ablation”) to capture some of these new lung surgery types that needed mapping (e.g., “Laser ablation or cryosurgery”, “Laser excision”, “Electrocautery; fulguration”). We discussed a few ways of applying the prioritization:
	<ul>
		<li>prioritizing the most radical surgery (e.g., the one most likely to be definitive)</li>
		<li>prioritizing by how much was removed during the surgery
		<ul>
			<li>When I looked up how we described this in the ADS DD: for lung, we prioritize surgical resections &gt; wedge. This variable is also intended to ‘indicate the procedure intended as surgical resection of the primary site as part of 1st course therapy’</li>
		</ul>
		</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li>Met again with Monika to clarify and we decided the ranking is by least to most radical (most radical is prioritized). Emailed Christer again with this definition and he provided the final rankings on <tt>2026-03-18</tt>.</li>
	<li>___ updated the actual <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1_2rAbT5obq_GbN4Dh1SciXf6QkidftFb0rM6rxxpz10/edit?gid=1562226994#gid=1562226994" class="external-link" rel="nofollow noreferrer">definitive_surgery_prioritization</a> tab from the ADS DD. ___ reran the code that pulls in the data from this google sheet into R.</li>
</ul>

  </td>
            </tr>
                                <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#f0f0f0" width="20%" valign="top"><b>Code Review:</b></td>
                <td id="customfield_12225-157760-value" class="value" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="80%"><div class="shorten" id="customfield_12225-field">
